rijk","Gunthorpe, North Norfolk, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Gunthorpe, Norfolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Brockley, Suffolk, England":"Brockley, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Brockley, Saint Edmundsbury district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Brockley, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1490–1525":"1490–1525","1494–1552":"1494–1552","1500–1552":"1500–1552","1512–1583":"1512–1583","1520–1547":"1520–1547","1460–Male":"1460–Deceased","1463–Female":"1463–Deceased","1583":"1583","1494":"1494","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","1525":"1525","1547":"1547","1512":"1512","Abt. 1515":"about 1515","1500":"1500","Abt 1520":"about 1520","1520":"1520","1552":"1552","1463":"1463","about 1511":"about 1511","Saint Andrew's Church, Brockley, Saint Edmundsbury district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"St Andrew's Church, Brockley, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Gunthorpe, North Norfolk, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Gunthorpe, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom","Brockley, Suffolk, England":"Brockley, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Brockley, Saint Edmundsbury district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Brockley, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Briston","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Norfolk and Rutland): habitational name from Briston in Norfolk, named from Old English <i>byrst</i> ‘burst, broken ground’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘enclosure, settlement’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Briston was born in 1490, in Gunthorpe, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom, her father, John Thomas Briston, was 30 and her mother, Catherine Hook, was 28. She married Sir John Davey about 1511, in Brockley, Suffolk, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1525, in Brockley, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 35, and was buried in St Andrew's Church, Brockley, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"1490–1525":"1490–1525","1494–1552":"1494–1552","1500–1552":"1500–1552","1512–1583":"1512–1583","1520–1547":"1520–1547","1460–Male":"1460–Surnud","1463–Female":"1463–Surnud","1583":"1583","1494":"1494","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","1525":"1525","1547":"1547","1512":"1512","Abt. 1515":"umbes 1515","1500":"1500","Abt 1520":"umbes 1520","1520":"1520","1552":"1552","1463":"1463","about 1511":"umbes 1511","Saint Andrew's Church, Brockley, Saint Edmundsbury district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"St Andrew's Church, Brockley, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Gunthorpe, North Norfolk, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Gunthorpe, Norfolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Brockley, Suffolk, England":"Brockley, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Brockley, Saint Edmundsbury district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Brockley, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1490–1525":"1490–1525","1494–1552":"1494–1552","1500–1552":"1500–1552","1512–1583":"1512–1583","1520–1547":"1520–1547","1460–Male":"1460–Kuollut","1463–Female":"1463–Kuollut","1583":"1583","1494":"1494","1460":"1460","1490":"1490","1525":"1525","1547":"1547","1512":"1512","Abt. 1515":"noin 1515","1500":"1500","Abt 1520":"noin 1520","1520":"1520","1552":"1552","1463":"1463","about 1511":"noin 1511","Saint Andrew's Church, Brockley, Saint Edmundsbury district, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"St Andrew's Church, Brockley, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Gunthorpe, North Norfolk, Norfolk, England, United Kingdom":"Gunthorpe, Norfolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Brockley, Suffolk, England":"Brockley, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Brockley, Saint Ed